  "rationale": "Cefoxitin (a 7-alpha-methoxy cephamycin) is stable to class A ESBLs like CTX-M-15, SHV-28, and TEM-1; their presence alone does not explain cefoxitin resistance. No AmpC (e.g., blaCMY, blaDHA, blaACT) or carbapenemase was reported by the annotators. The dominant visible mechanism is porin loss: OmpK35 carries a frameshift (G208VfsTer5) abolishing the major porin, and OmpK36 carries a loop-3 GD duplication (D135DGD) known to constrict the channel. Reduced outer membrane permeability, combined with periplasmic beta-lactamase activity acting as a weak sink, raises the cefoxitin MIC into the resistant range.",
  "uncertainty": "No AmpC-type beta-lactamase was reported in visible evidence; if a chromosomal/plasmid AmpC is present but missed, it would be the primary cefoxitin determinant. Validation: search assembly for blaCMY/blaDHA/blaACT/blaFOX with AMRFinderPlus --plus and BLAST; confirm ompK35 frameshift and ompK36 loop-3 insertion by ORF inspection.",
  "mechanism_class": "permeability_loss",
  "layers": {
    "genome": "Chromosomal porin lesions: ompK35 frameshift G208VfsTer5 and ompK36 loop-3 insertion D135DGD; plus acquired (likely plasmid) blaCTX-M-15, blaTEM-1, and chromosomal blaSHV-28. Plasmid vs chromosomal context not directly reported.",
    "protein": "OmpK35 and OmpK36 are 16-stranded beta-barrel outer membrane porins (OmpF/OmpC family). G208VfsTer5 truncates OmpK35 mid-barrel, abolishing a functional channel. D135DGD inserts a Gly-Asp dipeptide into loop L3 of OmpK36, the constriction loop, narrowing the eyelet. CTX-M-15/SHV-28/TEM-1 are class A serine beta-lactamases (alpha/beta hydrolase fold) with active-site Ser70.",
    "mechanism": "Permeability loss: truncated OmpK35 is not assembled into a functional channel; OmpK36 with loop-3 GD insertion has reduced cross-section and restricted diffusion of bulky beta-lactams (cefoxitin, carbapenems). Class A enzymes hydrolyze penicillins/cephalosporins via Ser70 acyl-enzyme but do not efficiently hydrolyze 7-alpha-methoxy cephamycins like cefoxitin.",
    "cell": "Porins reside in the outer membrane; their loss raises the diffusion barrier into the periplasm. Beta-lactamases reside in the periplasm where they would degrade any drug that does enter. Porin expression is regulated by OmpR/EnvZ and micF/MicC sRNAs, but here loss is structural (frameshift / loop insertion), not regulatory.",
    "phenotype": "Reduced outer membrane influx via OmpK35 loss and constricted OmpK36 lowers periplasmic cefoxitin concentration; even modest periplasmic beta-lactamase activity then suffices to keep PBP acylation below the lethal threshold, producing the observed cefoxitin-resistant AST phenotype."
  },
